<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="337" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="337">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="337">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Butler" authorityYear="1889" class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Pyralis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pyralis princeps" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="princeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">Pyralis princeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from four specimens collected in India (Himachal Pradesh, Dharamshala [Dharmsala]) and two from 
<normalizedToken originalValue="”Yezo”">&quot;Yezo&quot;</normalizedToken>
[region from Northern Japan to Kamchatka] (Butler, 1889). However, the latter two are misidentifications of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. cardinalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" rank="species" species="cardinalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">P. cardinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this interpretation also supported by our examination of some Japanese and South Korean specimens. Following 
<bibRefCitation author="ICZN" journalOrPublisher="The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" refId="B10" refString="ICZN, 1999. International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition. The International Trust for Zoological Nomenclature, London" title="International Code of Zoological Nomenclature. Fourth edition." year="1999">ICZN (1999)</bibRefCitation>
, a lectotype from Dharamshala [Dharmsala], already labelled as such by M. Shaffer in NHMUK, is here designated in order to fix the identity of the species and conserve nomenclatural stability.We have examined photographs of the specimen and its labels which confirm our interpretation. Outside Europe, the name 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. princeps" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" rank="species" species="princeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">P. princeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Butler has been somewhat inconsistently used for the East Palearctic populations. E.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Shibuya, J" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Hokkaido Imperial University" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" pagination="149 - 176" refId="B24" refString="Shibuya, J, 1928. The systematic study on the Japanese Pyralinae (Lepid.). Journal of the Faculty of Agriculture, Hokkaido Imperial University 21 (4): 149 - 176" title="The systematic study on the Japanese Pyralinae (Lepid.)." volume="21" year="1928">Shibuya (1928)</bibRefCitation>
, in his treatment of Japanese species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Pyralidae" genus="Pyralis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pyralis" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">Pyralis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and related genera, only recognized 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. regalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" rank="species" species="regalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">P. regalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of the relevant taxa to occur there. Inoue 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">et al.</emphasis>
(1982), plate 46: Figs 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 4–11" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 4 - 11. Pyralis sp., habitus. 4 - 7. P. cardinalis sp. nov., 4. ♂, Finland, V, Kemioensaari, leg. J. Tyllinen. 5. ♀, A, Lemland, leg. B. Wikstroem &amp; K. Vaalamo; 6. ♂, Finland, U, Kirkkonummi, leg. J. Junnilainen; 7. ♂, Finland, U, Raasepori, leg. L. Kaila. 8 - 11. P. regalis. 8. ♂, Greece, Lesvos, leg. L. Kaila &amp; J. Kullberg. 9. ♀, Slovenia, Granska Gora, leg. B. Wikstroem; 10. ♂, Italy, Tuscany, Cortona, leg. B. Wikstroem. 11. Bulgaria, 5 km S. Blagoevgrad, ♀, leg. B. A. Bengtsson." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.54916.figures4-11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473649" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">4</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figures 4–11" captionStartId="F4" captionText="Figures 4 - 11. Pyralis sp., habitus. 4 - 7. P. cardinalis sp. nov., 4. ♂, Finland, V, Kemioensaari, leg. J. Tyllinen. 5. ♀, A, Lemland, leg. B. Wikstroem &amp; K. Vaalamo; 6. ♂, Finland, U, Kirkkonummi, leg. J. Junnilainen; 7. ♂, Finland, U, Raasepori, leg. L. Kaila. 8 - 11. P. regalis. 8. ♂, Greece, Lesvos, leg. L. Kaila &amp; J. Kullberg. 9. ♀, Slovenia, Granska Gora, leg. B. Wikstroem; 10. ♂, Italy, Tuscany, Cortona, leg. B. Wikstroem. 11. Bulgaria, 5 km S. Blagoevgrad, ♀, leg. B. A. Bengtsson." figureDoi="10.3897/nl.43.54916.figures4-11" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/473649" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">5</figureCitation>
illustrated Japanese specimens that seem identical to 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. cardinalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" rank="species" species="cardinalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">P. cardinalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and whose occurrence in Japan is verified in the present study. Neither of these authors mention other species, but they consider 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. princeps" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" rank="species" species="princeps">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">P. princeps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a synonym of 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. regalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="337" rank="species" species="regalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="337">P. regalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
